Pollock Effort

JW pulled this data from AKFIN see data/AK_Effort_Trawl/Gasper Data/Chinook_Bycatch_Data_Description (2).htmlfor more specific query info.

General methods:

First half of sample fraction- How many boat days are observed?

Total Effort Data: We have data on total effort for 1991-2017. Shoreside/CV fish tickets for the GOA only. JW removed the CPs because they dont always issue fish tickets. They instead track their landings via production reports.

Observed data: Jordan counted the number of unique haul_dates for each vessel-sector-trip_target_code-year-nmfsarea-month combo, so we have a summary of all observed hauls, and this is summarised into boat days by taking the . For Shoreside delivers, that is based on your sample fraction (ie still a fraction of effort still unobserved). Note that this still doesnt identify which deliveries were made to tenders (which of course, are not observed, GS has this data from else where and can match in, only occurs after 2006). Jordan created a trip_target_code2 that is non-P when gear is NPT because of 1996 ambiguity, recomends we skip 1996 because there are a bunch of trips (N=327) where trip target code is missing. However, we know that if gear type is NPT (non-pelagic trawl), it is not a pollock target. So we will say that if trip_target_code is missing but gear is NPT then trip_target_code is not pollock (Not-P). This leaves us a trivial number of missing trip_target_code in all years but 1996. Data from 1996 is included in this data set but only by filter out NPT gear, so it likely overestimates effort.

1991-1995: We do not have direct observed effort infomation here, so instead I used the observer coverage chart in our google drive, to estimate the fraciton of total effort that was observed from 1991-1995. This is VERY likely an overestimate, so we may want to take it out.
1996-2017: We have information on observed trips. Trip-level data is provided, but we have fishing start and landing dates, so by subtracting those we get an estimate of boat days. Jordan is concerned with this because landed date not necessarily equal to when they came into port nor when they stopped fishing, likely they dont land fish the same day they stopped fishing, likely more than a day, shorter the trip the more liklihood for error.

Second half of sample fraction- If there is an observer on board how many fish are the checking for CWT? Observer protocols: Observers sample 100% of catch for Chinook and then check 1/10 chinook for a CWT (Jordan is unsure when this policy started, suggested we just use it for the whole time). Bascially 10% of catch is surveyed for CWT, unless the deliver goes to a tender, than 0% of catch is checked for CWT.

If there is an observer on board- how much of the catch are they surveying? 10% unless a vessel delivers to a tender, than 0% Below is a summary of fraction of total Chinook sampled per trip, given there is an observer onboard. Any fraction less than 10% means that some trips during that month were delivered to a tender.

This data comes from Chinooky_rates_merged.RDS, the tender delivery difference only started after ~2010 so these data are appropriate to use, earlier years are 10%
